ENDF/B-VII.1 EVALUATION MODIFICATIONS 2/27/2011 P.G.Young, P.Talou, T. Kawano, M.B.Chadwick, (LANL)
----- SUMMARY -----
The ENDF/B-VII.1 evaluation is a modification of the ENDF/B- VII.0 evaluation to correct the cross sections and angular distributions of the ground-state rotational band of 233U, i.e., MF=3,4, MT=51,52,53,55,58,65. The correction was required because the compound-nucleus components for these states in the Version VIII.0 evaluation did not take proper account of fission competition. In addition, the inelastic cross section below 1 MeV exhibited an anomalous peak, mainly due to MT=51,52. The following changes were made:
1. The compound nucleus cross sections for MT=51,52,53,55,58,65 were re-calculated and combined with the direct components from ECIS calculations. 2. The MF=4, MT=53,55,58,65 data were replaced with these data. 3. The MF=3, MT=53,55,58,65 data were also replaced with these data. 4. The corrected results for MF=3,4, MT=51,52 were found to inadequately reproduce the measurements of Haouat et. al (Ha82 below). It was surmised that the deformed optical model potential used in the evaluation might not be adequate at incident energies below approximately 1.0-1.5 MeV. Therefore, to correct this problem, the compound nucleus contributions to these states were scaled by a single factor to produce better agreement with the Haouat et al. experiment. The difference in the inelastic cross section was absorbed in the elastic cross section. 5. The data were modified for MF=3,4, MT=2,51,52 (the MT=2 change was small).

ENDF/B-VII EVALUATION
P.G.Young, M.B.Chadwick, R.E.MacFarlane, W.B.Wilson, D.G.Madland, P.Talou, T. Kawano (LANL) and L. Leal, H. Derrien, Guber, N. Larson, R. Wright, R.Spencer (ORNL)
----- SUMMARY ----- The ENDF/B-VII evaluation is a complete revision of almost all the data in the 233U evaluation. Major features of the evaluation are: 1. A new evaluation of the (n,f) cross section based on ENDF/B- VII standard cross section analysis is incorporated. 2. A new evaluation of nubar consistent with experimental data within uncertainties and with fast critical benchmark measurements is included. 3. New resolved and unresolved resonance parameter data are incorporated. 4. Improved delayed neutron data are incorporated. 5. Coupled-channels optical model calculations are used to provide scattering cross sections and angular distributions. 6. New reaction theory calculations are utilized for (n,xn) and other reactions. 7. Compound nucleus and direct reaction cross sections and angular distributions are extended to an excitation energy of 1.5 MeV. 8. Fission neutron spectra from JENDL-3.3 are adopted. 9. Covariance matrix evaluations for all energy ranges.
----- DETAILED DESCRIPTION -----
>> MF=1 GENERAL INFORMATION
MT=452: TOTAL AVERAGE NEUTRON MULTIPLICITY PER FISSION (TOTAL NUBAR) Sum of MT=455 and 456. Adopted the ENDF/B-VII thermal standard value of 2.4968.
MT=455: AVERAGE DELAYED NEUTRON MULTIPLICITY PER FISSION Based on new delayed neutron 6-group parameters from CINDER'90 summation calculations. The CINDER calculations (Wi05) are based on a new CINDER library in which beta-decay half-lives and beta- delayed neutron-emission probablities are obtained from the evaluated experimental data file NuBase2003 (Au03), when available there. When experimental data are not available, the data are calculated in a model where allowed Gamow-Teller decays are treated in a microscopic quasi-particle random-phase approximation (QRPA) and the first forbidden decays are treated in the statistical gross theory (Mo03). (typo fixed by TK 2009)
MT=456: AVERAGE PROMPT NEUTRON MULTIPLICITY PER FISSION 1.e-5 eV - 10 eV: Adopted the thermal value of 2.4894 for prompt nubar, corresponding to the ENDF/B-VII thermal standard value of 2.4968 for total nubar. 10 eV - 30 MeV: Generally based on results from the covariance analysis of experimental data performed for ENDF/B-VI, after correction for the ENDF/B-VII standard 252Cf nubar value. We attempted to follow the covariance data as well as possible but mainly to stay within uncertainties in the data and to keep good agreement with fast critical benchmarks.

>> MF=2 RESONANCE PARAMETERS
MT=151 RESOLVED AND UNRESOLVED RESONANCE PARAMETER EVALUATIONS L. Leal, H. Derrien, Guber, N. Larson, R. Wright, and R.Spencer (ORNL) January, 2003
The resonance parameter evaluation was done by Leal, Derrien, Guber, Larson, Wright and Spencer [LE01] using the multilevel R-matrix analysis code SAMMY [LA96]. The resolved resonance evaluation were performed in the energy range from 0 to 600 eV. The unresolved resonance region evaluation covers the energy range from 600 eV to 40 keV. The evaluation included high resolution transmission data (GU00), fission cross section data [GU98] measured at the Oak Ridge Electron Linear Accelerator (ORELA), in addition to other experimental data. >> MF=3 NEUTRON CROSS SECTIONS
----- GENERAL INFORMATION -----
EVALUATION ABOVE THE UNRESOLVED RESONANCE REGION P. G. Young and M. B. Chadwick (LANL) January, 2003 The maximum energy of the evaluation (Yo03) was increased to 30 MeV. Above the unresolved resonance region (En=40 keV), new evaluations were performed of the neutron total, elastic, (n,n'), (n,2n), (n,3n), (n,4n), (n,f), (n,nf), (n,2nf), (n,3nf), (n,4nf), and (n,gamma) cross sections, as well as their associated angular and energy distributions. The energy range of the evaluation was increased from 20 to 30 MeV. To provide the new data, coupled channel optical model calcu- lations were performed with the ECIS96 code for the lowest 7 members of the U233 ground state rotational band. These calcu- lations were used to provide elastic and inelastic cross sections and angular distributions, and to provide neutron transmission coefficients for nuclear reaction theory calculations with the GNASH (Ch01,Yo98) Hauser- Feshbach statistical/fission/ preequilibrium code. The GNASH calculations were used directly for the correlated energy-angle spectra in MF=6 for the (n,n'continuum), (n,2n), (n,3n), and (n,4n) reactions. The total cross section (MT=1), the radiative capture cross section (MT=102) and the fission cross section (MT=18) are based all or in part on experimental data. Experimental data were obtained mainly from the EXFOR data base. All other cross sections are based on theoretical calculations. In addition, the shape of the radiative capture cross section at lower energies and the absolute values above 1 MeV are from the GNASH analysis.
----- DETAILS OF LANL REVISION -----
MT=1: TOTAL CROSS SECTION The ENDF/B-VI evaluation of the total cross section (MT=1), based mainly on experimental data but especially [Fo71], was adopted over the energy range 1-15 MeV. The ENDF/B-VI results were modified slightly below 1 MeV to better conform with experimental data. The optical model analysis (Yo03) was used for the cross section from 15 to 30 MeV.
MT=2: ELASTIC SCATTERING CROSS SECTION The elastic cross section is obtained by subtracting the nonelastic cross section (MT=3) from the total cross section (MT=1).
MT=3: NONELASTIC CROSS SECTION The (redundant) nonelastic cross section is the sum of the following reactions: MT=4,16,17,18,37,102.
MT=4: INELASTIC CROSS SECTION Sum of MT=51-91.
MT=16,17,37: (n,xn) CROSS SECTIONS The (n,xn) cross sections are based on an analysis with the GNASH nuclear model code (Yo98). The (n,5n) cross section becomes significant above about 25 MeV. Because there is no ENDF-6 MT number for this reaction, we have arbitrarily included this cross section in the (n,4n) reaction. Consequently, the (n,4n) cross section becomes unphysical above about 25 MeV.
MT=18: FISSION NEUTRON CROSS SECTION Much of the 233U fission cross section data are in the form of ratios relative to 235U. All 233U(n,f) ratio and cross section data were converted to ENDF/B-VII standards [see Pronyaev et al. (Pr05)], and a covariance analysis of the data was performed. The results were smoothed and used for the (n,f) cross section, after small modifications. The somewhat higher 235U fission cross section in the fission spectrum region produces better agreement with with fast critical benchmark experiments. Important experimental data included in the ENDF/B-VII analysis include the data of Li02, Me74, Me88, and Ka86.
MT=19,20,21,38: MULTI-CHANCE FISSION CROSS SECTIONS The ratios of the multi-chance fission cross sections to the total fission cross section were obtained from GNASH calculations. The evaluated multi-chance fission cross sections were then obtained by multiplying the MT=18 total fission cross section by the ratios.
MT=51-53,55,58,65: DISCRETE INELASTIC CROSS SECTIONS TO GROUND- STATE ROTATIONAL BAND LEVELS Coupled channel optical model calculations were performed with the ECIS96 code for the lowest 7 members of the U233 ground state rotational band (MT=2,51,52,53,55,58,65), including compound nucleus contributions. These calculations were also used to provide neutron transmission coefficients for nuclear reaction theory calculations with the GNASH (Yo98) and COMNUC (Du71) Hauser- Feshbach statistical-fission-preequilibrium codes. See description above under GENERAL INFORMATION.
MT=54,56-57,59-64,66-88: DISCRETE INELASTIC NEUTRON CROSS SECTIONS Inelastic cross sections from compound-nucleus reactions were calculated with ECIS96 for all states. In addition, ECIS96 was used for vibrational model calculations for 3- and 2+ states in 238U which were then included in lumped form in the 233U analysis (MT=84-88).
MT=91: INELASTIC CONTINUUM NEUTRON CROSS SECTION Based on the GNASH Hauser-Feshbach statistical-preequilibrium calculations, described above. Note that MT=91 thresholds at 0.70 MeV. Therefore, discrete states with excitation energies above 0.70 MeV (MT=83-88) lie in the MT=91 continuum region.
MT=102: NEUTRON RADIATIVE CAPTURE CROSS SECTION 1.0-5 to 40 keV: Based on the resonance parameter evaluation by Leal et al. (see above). 40 keV to 30 MeV: The GNASH code system was utilized to calculate the (n,gamma) cross section from 1 keV to 16 MeV. The gamma-ray strength function and level densities were adjusted so that the calculation reproduced the experimental data of Hopkins and Diven (Ho62). The results were used from 0.04 to 16 MeV for the (n,gamma) cross section, with a smooth extrapolation to 30 MeV.

>> MF=4 ANGULAR DISTRIBUTIONS OF SECONDARY PARTICLES
MT=2: NEUTRON ELASTIC SCATTERING ANGULAR DISTRIBUTIONS All elastic neutron angular distributions are based on the coupled-channels optical model calculations with the ECIS96 code (Ra94), including compound elastic contributions. The optical model results are in good agreement with the experimental data of Ha82.

>> MF=5 ENERGY DISTRIBUTIONS OF SECONDARY PARTICLES
MT=18: Prompt Fission Neutron Spectrum Matrix The MT=18 spectra are taken from the JENDL-3.3 evaluation (Ma02). That evaluation utilizes a modified form (Oh92) of the Madland and Nix Los Alamos model (MN82). The compound nucleus formation cross sections for fission fragments (FF) were calculated using Becchetti-Greenlees potential (Be69). Up to 4th-chance-fission were considered at high incident neuttron energies. The Ignatyuk formula (Ig79) were used to generate the level density parameters. Parameters adopted: Total average FF kinetic energy = 172.311-0.0212*E(MeV) Average energy release = 188.438 MeV Average mass number of light FF = 95 Average mass number of heavy FF = 139 Level density of the light FF = 9.999- 10.094 Level density of the heavy FF = 11.89 - 12.20 Note that the parameters vary with the incident energy within the indicated range.
MT=455: DELAYED NEUTRON EMISSION SPECTRA FROM FISSION The abundances are based on the new delayed-neutron calculations (Wi05) described under MF=1, MT=455. However, the earlier six-group spectra from ENDF/B-VI are carried over to ENDF/B-VII because new multigroup spectra have not yet been calculated with the new library.

>> MF=33 CROSS-SECTION COVARIANCE MATRICES
>>> MF=33 RESONANCE PARAMETER COVARIANCE (ORNL)
Resonance parameter covariances were generated in the resolved energy region (1.0-5 eV to 600.0 eV) with the computer code SAMMY at ORNL. Uncertainty on nubar was also generated at ORNL. Experimental data and uncertainties were used to generate covariance data. SAMMY covariance information was converted in the ENDF FILE32 representation. However, because of computer storage concern the FILE32 was converted into the FILE33 (MT=1, 2, 18, and 102) representation with reduced computer storage but approximating the features of the FILE32 representation. The full FILE32 matrices can be obtained directly from ORNL. The conversion was done with the PUFF-IV code. Above the unresolved resonance region ( > 40 keV) covariance data were generated at LANL.
>>> MF=33 FAST-ENERGY COVARIANCE (LANL)
Cross-section covariance matrices in the fast energy region were obtained through a combination of nuclear reaction sensitivity calculations using the GNASH code, and available information on experimental uncertainties for some of the cross sections. The sensitivity of GNASH results on the choice of model parameters was assessed, and the KALMAN code (Ka97) was used to merge sensitivity calculations with experimental uncertainties.
More details on this work can be found in (Ta08).
